comments.text: I find the format to be a bit disrespectful but to tell the truth it's been 11 years and we still don't have an answer to what happened. I'm happy that someone finally actually went there and recorded all the locations as well as tried to talk to as many people as they could. Staying overnight in that jungle must have been pretty scary and to tell the truth I am not as certain as everyone else seems to be that someone couldn't get lost there under such circumstances. Just a few of my thoughts on the matter; I wouldn't confidently disregard the theory that the girls went missing on the other side of El Mirador simply because one of the villagers said the picture wasn't from that side of the mountain. To be frank, there really isn't any way of him being so familiar with a 14+ hour long trail that he could rule out a specific location with any certainty. I'm guessing the phones were not geo-located since no one knows exactly where the calls were made from, but as the two journalists said, the trail on the Pianista side of the mountain is pretty heavily populated with houses and private properties. Does it seem likely that they were ambushed in an area where people are literally looking at you from their bedroom windows? Also, they started their hike around 11 and were at the mountain summit at 1 pm, so it took them two hours to go uphill; the first emergency call was made at 4:39 PM, so realistically they would have been off the trail by that time (especially since they were going downhill). Second, the little branch on the rock with red material attached to it seems to have part of trail markers that were attached to the branches of a tree. I don't know if there were multiple such markers on the trail or if only one location had them, but if you look up drone footage of the other side of the mountain there is a really tall tree with these little red flags attached to the tops of it's branches near the first monkey bridge on the trail. The bridge itself is different from the one in this video, though the drone footage was shot much later;  it seems to have been updated to be more safe since then and the flow of water was minimal. Looking at the drone footage initially it seemed hard to believe that a fall from this bridge would likely be fatal, especially since the flow of the water was minimal and one could quite easily hop over to the other side from one rock to the next. If this is the same river, however, and the heavy flow is due to it being wet season then it's easy to see how dangerous it would be falling in there.  I disagree with some of the 'experts' that such a fall would certainly be fatal or necessarily resolute in a fractured pelvis or broken neck. That certainly could happen, but it really depends on how they fell in; at what angle and if they had a chance to grab onto something before falling etc. So, finally... what do I think could have happened? This is just a theory but I feel it's plausible given the evidence. The girls thought that the trail looped around the mountain and went down the other side. Maybe they didn't check the map correctly prior to setting out, maybe someone along the way had told them something along these lines/they misunderstood, maybe the trail confused them because it seemed to turn before going down again so they thought they had turned around. Either way, they walked for nearly 4 hours in that direction which is twice what it had taken them to get up. At that point, they were probably fairly certain they had gone the wrong way. This was early April in Panama, so sunset would have been around 6 pm which wouldn't have given them much time before it was dark. I think this is when they panicked and called emergency services, but instead of turning around they kept going forward. I think they didn't make it to the monkey bridge before dark and by the time they did get there they were in enough of a panic to attempt to cross it. Did they fall? Most likely. If they had made it across, chances are they would have finally made the 14 hour long journey towards more populated areas where the villagers and natives lived. I think at least one of them survived, most likely Lisanne, though perhaps both. Lisanne broke her foot from the fall and the water most likely swept both of them down the river. They probably stayed in that area, not too far from this bridge for a while. By April 8th, whoever was taking those photos was by that bridge, in the middle of the night. I'm not quite sure how the search parties wouldn't have come across them unless they didn't search that area until after they were gone. Maybe Lisanne/Kris couldn't get back up out of the river with their injuries and kept going upriver to try to find an easier way up. Maybe their injuries were so severe they couldn't really move from where the river had swept them up. Either way, it's terrifying and still doesn't fully make sense why they weren't found if those night photos on the 8th were taken so close to the monkey bridge which is on the trail.

comments.text:
This show is a disgrace.
Lost in the Wild: Hike Into Hell isnt an investigation  its true-crime necrophilia. No new evidence, no answers, just recycled internet theories, ominous music, and self-important nobodies profiting off the deaths of Kris Kremers and Lisanne Froon.

The cast arent investigators, theyre content scavengers, hinting at foul play without proof because insinuation gets clicks. All theyve done is fuel conspiracies, smear locals, and ensure the families never get peace.

These were real women, not props for your brand.
Turning their deaths into episodic suspense is moral grave-robbing.

This isnt about truth.
Its about views.
And its an insult to their memory.
